============================================================
                 JAVA → SPRING FRAMEWORK NOTES
============================================================

1. JAVA DOMAIN – 3 CATEGORIES
------------------------------------------------------------

In the Java domain, there are 3 categories of subjects to learn:

------------------------------------------------------------
a) JAVA LANGUAGE
------------------------------------------------------------
- Core Java course
- Acts as raw material for Java programming
- Like rice/wheat (raw items)

Using the Java language:
- We develop only standalone applications
- 80% programmer written code
- 20% ready-made libraries

Examples:
- Core Java
- OOPs
- Exception Handling
- Multithreading


------------------------------------------------------------
b) JAVA TECHNOLOGIES
------------------------------------------------------------
- Advanced Java course
- Acts as semi-finished products
- Like rice flour / wheat flour

Using Java technologies:
- We develop web applications / websites
- 40% ready-made facilities
- 60% programmer written code

Examples:
- JDBC
- Servlet
- JSP
- JNDI
- JTA


------------------------------------------------------------
c) JAVA FRAMEWORKS
------------------------------------------------------------
- Spring, Spring Boot course
- Acts as fully finished products
- Like instant foods (Maggi / noodles)

Using Java frameworks:
- Standalone applications
- Web applications
- Distributed applications
- Enterprise applications

Code usage:
- 80% ready-made facilities
- 20% programmer written code

Examples:
- Struts
- JSF
- Spring
- Spring Boot
- Hibernate
- WebWork


------------------------------------------------------------
2. LAYERED VIEW
------------------------------------------------------------

Developer
   |
Java Application / Project
   |
Java Framework (Spring / Spring Boot)
   |
Java Technologies (JDBC, Servlet, JSP, ...)
   |
Java Language


------------------------------------------------------------
3. RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN THEM
------------------------------------------------------------

- Java Frameworks are built on top of Java Technologies
  Examples:
  -> Struts, JSF, Spring, Spring Boot, Hibernate, iBatis

- Java Technologies are built on top of Java Language
  Examples:
  -> JDBC, Servlet, JSP, JNDI, JTA

- Java Language defines:
  -> Syntax (rules)
  -> Semantics (structure)
  -> Compilers and Interpreters


============================================================
4. FRAMEWORK – DEFINITION
============================================================

Definition 1:
Framework is a special installable software that provides
abstraction on one or more technologies and lets developers
write only application specific logic.

Definition 2:
Framework hides unnecessary details and exposes only
necessary details to simplify application development.

This concept is called ABSTRACTION.


------------------------------------------------------------
5. WHAT IS ABSTRACTION?
------------------------------------------------------------

- Hiding unnecessary implementation details
- Exposing only required features to developers
- Every framework internally uses technologies
- Programmer does NOT need to know internal logic


------------------------------------------------------------
6. FRAMEWORK EXAMPLES
------------------------------------------------------------

Java Frameworks:
- Struts
- JSF
- Spring
- Spring Boot
- WebWork
- Hibernate
- iBatis

.NET Frameworks:
- ASP.NET
- .NET Core

Python Frameworks:
- Django
- Flask

JavaScript Frameworks:
- Angular
- ExpressJS


============================================================
7. TECHNOLOGY BASED APP – JDBC EXAMPLE
============================================================

Sample JDBC Application (Technology App)

------------------------------------------------------------
COMMON LOGICS:
------------------------------------------------------------
- Load JDBC driver
- Establish DB connection
- Create JDBC Statement
- Handle Exceptions
- Close DB connection

------------------------------------------------------------
APPLICATION-SPECIFIC LOGICS:
------------------------------------------------------------
- Send SQL query to DB
- Execute query
- Get results
- Process results


Problems:
- Developer must write both common and application logic
- Code repetition across projects
- Boilerplate code problem


------------------------------------------------------------
8. BOILERPLATE CODE PROBLEM
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:
- Code that repeats in multiple projects
- Code that changes very little or not at all
- Increases developer burden
- Reduces productivity


============================================================
9. SPRING JDBC APP (FRAMEWORK BASED)
============================================================

Spring JDBC App uses:
- JdbcTemplate class

Spring takes care of:
- Driver loading
- Connection handling
- Statement creation
- Exception handling
- Resource closing

Developer writes only:
- SQL queries
- Business logic
- Result processing


------------------------------------------------------------
10. ADVANTAGE OF SPRING FRAMEWORK
------------------------------------------------------------

- No boilerplate code
- Framework generates common logic dynamically
- Developer focuses only on application-specific logic
- Faster development
- Cleaner code
- Better maintainability


